ting Vermont farmland. He bought a farm in Essex County NY for twelve years; in 1847 bought the 166-acre Goodale farm in Addison County; in 1854 moved to Weybridge and bought the 50-acre Lawrence place. At peak he owned over five hundred acres across multiple Addison County farms — matching the size of his father Abel's original homestead."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Remarried at seventy-three to Jane's birthday","body":"Calvin's first wife Sarah Sargeant died November 1884 after forty-nine years of marriage. Four months later, on March 19, 1885 — Jane Sargent's forty-third birthday — Calvin married her, daughter of Samuel Sargent of Middlebury. Calvin was seventy-three; Jane was thirty years his junior."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"Three children only Calvin Jr survived","body":"Calvin and Sarah Sargeant had three children — one daughter and two sons. Only the youngest son, Calvin Junior, survived to adulthood. The local history does not name the two children who died young."}],"quotes":[],"sources":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"slug":"calvin-norton-1811"}},"burialCemetery":null,"institutionsById":{},"crossConnections":[]}